    <h2>Section A: Long Answer Question:
Attempt any two questions:</h2><h3>Question 1</h3>
<div><p><p>What do you mean by the contact potential? Give a schematic of a p-n Junction by illustrating:</p>
<ul>
<li>(a) Potential difference V, resulting from the positive donor ions in the n-side of the depletion layer and the negative acceptor ions in the p-side of the depletion layer.</li>
<li>(b) Potential energy barrier faced by the majority charge carriers (electrons) in the n-side of the diode as they attempt to cross the junction.</li>
<li>(c) Potential energy barrier faced by the majority side of the diode as they attempt to cross the junction.</li>
</ul</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Contact Potential in a P-N Junction:</strong></p>
<p>Potential difference in a p-n junction is the potential difference which arises across the junction when a p-type semiconductor (with a high hole concentration as charge carriers) is brought in contact with an n-type semiconductor (with an excess of electrons). This potential difference is created due to the diffusion of charge carriers from one side to the other, creating an electric field and a depletion region free of free charge carriers.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>When the p-type and n-type materials are brought together, electrons from the n-side diffuse into the p-side and combine with holes. Similarly, holes from the p-side diffuse into the n-side. This results in the creation of an electric field, which causes the positive donor ions on the n-side and the negative acceptor ions on the p-side to create a built-in potential difference. This contact potential is the potential difference and plays a crucial role in determining the behavior of the junction in devices like diodes.</p>
<p><strong>Schematic of a P-N Junction with Explanations</strong></p>
<p>Below is a breakdown of the schematic depicting the p-n junction, along with explanations of the contact potential and potential energy barriers that the charge carriers face.</p>
<p><img class="aligncenter" /><img class="aligncenter" /></p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-57201" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/qn1physics.jpg?resize=1075%2C716&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="1075" height="716"></p>
<p><strong>(a) Potential Difference (V) Due to Donor and Acceptor Ions:</strong></p>
<p>Because of the diffusion of charge carriers within depletion region between n-side and p-side of the junction, positive donor ions on the n-side and negative acceptor ions on the p-side are formed. The separation of charges results in an electric field and a potential difference across the junction. This potential difference ‘V’ or the contact potential. It opposes further diffusion of electrons and holes, basically stopping them from freely crossing the junction.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>(b) Potential Energy Barrier to Electrons on the N-side:</strong></p>
<p>Electrons are the majority charge carriers in the n-side of the junction. When these electrons attempt to cross the junction to the p-side, they must overcome the potential energy barrier offered by the contact potential. This obstacle is the energy that has to be used up for an electron to move from the n-side, through the depletion region, and into the p-side. This potential energy barrier is the cause for the absence of free flow of electrons from the n-side to the p-side under no applied voltage.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>(c) Potential Energy Barrier for Holes in the P-side</strong></p>
<p>Holes are the dominant charge carriers in the p-side of the junction. Since these holes attempt to diffuse to the n-side, they face an equivalent potential energy barrier as the electrons. This barrier prevents the holes from freely diffusing from the p-side to the n-side. An external voltage (forward bias) needs to be overcome by the potential energy barrier so that current can be forced to flow through the junction.</p>
<p>Contact potential is a result of charge carrier diffusion through the p-n junction, forming an electric field that prevents further diffusion. The hole and electron potential energy barriers are energies that majority carriers must diffuse through the junction in order to allow current to flow. The diagram provided does serve to make these matters more visually clear by depicting the depletion region and charges that create the contact potential.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 2</h3>
<div><p><p>Discuss single crystal growth by discussing the following techniques:</p>
<ul>
<li>(a) Czochralski Method,</li>
<li>(b) Bridgman-Stockbarger Method,</li>
<li>(c) Floating Zone Method, and</li>
<li>(d) Vapor-Phase Epitaxy.</li>
</ul</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><h4><strong>1. Czochralski Method</strong></h4>
<p>The Czochralski method is a widely used technique for growing single crystals, especially for semiconductors like silicon. Here’s how it works:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>A seed crystal is dipped into a melt of the material (e.g., silicon) in a crucible.</li>
<li>The seed crystal is slowly rotated and pulled upward while the melt is cooled.</li>
<li>As the seed is pulled, the material solidifies into a single crystal with the same orientation as the seed.</li>
<li>This method is used to produce large, high-quality crystals for the semiconductor industry.</li>
</ul>
<h4><strong>2. Bridgman-Stockbarger Method</strong></h4>
<p>The Bridgman-Stockbarger method is used to grow single crystals of materials like semiconductors, metals, and optical crystals. The process involves:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Placing the material in a crucible with a pointed end.</li>
<li>Heating the crucible in a furnace to melt the material.</li>
<li>Slowly moving the crucible through a temperature gradient, causing the material to solidify from the pointed end.</li>
<li>The slow cooling and controlled solidification result in a single crystal.</li>
</ul>
<h4><strong>3. Floating Zone Method</strong></h4>
<p>The floating zone method is used to grow high-purity single crystals, especially for materials like silicon and germanium. The process involves:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>A polycrystalline rod of the material is held vertically.</li>
<li>A small zone of the rod is melted using a heating source (e.g., a laser or RF coil).</li>
<li>The molten zone is moved along the rod, and as it cools, it solidifies into a single crystal.</li>
<li>This method avoids contamination from crucibles, making it ideal for high-purity applications.</li>
</ul>
<h4><strong>4. Vapor-Phase Epitaxy</strong></h4>
<p>Vapor-phase epitaxy (VPE) is a technique used to grow thin single-crystal layers on a substrate. The process involves:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Introducing gaseous precursors of the material into a reaction chamber.</li>
<li>The precursors react on the surface of a heated substrate, forming a single-crystal layer.</li>
<li>This method is used to grow materials like gallium arsenide (GaAs) and silicon carbide (SiC) for electronic and optoelectronic devices.</li>
</ul>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class=" wp-image-52641 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/Screenshot-2025-03-01-113220.png?resize=521%2C586&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="521" height="586"> <img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class=" wp-image-52642 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/Screenshot-2025-03-01-113232.png?resize=568%2C441&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="568" height="441"> <img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class=" wp-image-52643 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/Screenshot-2025-03-01-113324.png?resize=425%2C505&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="425" height="505"> <img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-52644 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/Screenshot-2025-03-01-113338.png?resize=495%2C401&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="495" height="401"></p>
</div>
<h3>Question 3</h3>
<div><p><p>Describe torque on a current-carrying rectangular loop of wire on a pivot rod when placed in a magnetic field. Give an alternative way of increasing the torque on the coil.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-52638" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/Screenshot-2025-03-01-104816.png?resize=657%2C938&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="657" height="938"></p>
<h3></h3>
<p>To increase the torque on the coil, we can:</p>
<ol start="1">
<li><strong>Increase the Current (<span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">I</span></span></span></span>)</strong>: The torque is directly proportional to the current. Increasing the current will increase the torque.</li>
<li><strong>Increase the Area (<span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">A</span></span></span></span>)</strong>: A larger loop area will result in a larger torque.</li>
<li><strong>Increase the Magnetic Field (<span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">B</span></span></span></span>)</strong>: A stronger magnetic field will increase the torque.</li>
<li><strong>Adjust the Angle (<span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">θ</span></span></span></span>)</strong>: The torque is maximum when <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">θ=90∘</span></span> (loop perpendicular to the field). Adjusting the loop to this angle will maximize the torque.</li>
</ol>
</div>
<h2>Section B : Short answer questions
Attempt any Eight Questions</h2><h3>Question 4</h3>
<div><p><p>Explain group velocity.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><div class="dad65929">
<div class="f9bf7997 d7dc56a8 c05b5566">
<div class="ds-markdown ds-markdown--block">
<p>Group velocity is the speed at which the <strong>overall shape</strong> (envelope) of a group of waves travels. It tells us how fast the energy or information in a wave moves.</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Wave Packet</strong>: A group of waves with slightly different frequencies forms a &#8220;wave packet.&#8221; The group velocity is the speed of this packet.</li>
<li><strong>Phase Velocity</strong>: This is the speed of individual wave crests. Group velocity and phase velocity are different in most materials.</li>
<li><strong>Formula</strong>: Group velocity <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">vg=dω/dk</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, where <span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">ω</span></span></span></span> is the wave&#8217;s frequency and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">k</span></span> is the wave number.</li>
</ul>
<h4></h4>
<p><strong>Example </strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Prism Example</strong>: When light passes through a prism, it splits into colors because different colors travel at different speeds. The group velocity is the speed of the overall light beam, while the phase velocity is the speed of each color.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Why it matters</strong></p>
<p>Group velocity is important in communication (e.g., how fast signals travel in fiber optics) and in understanding wave behavior in materials.</p>
<p><strong>Hence</strong>, Group velocity is the speed of the wave&#8217;s &#8220;envelope.&#8221; It’s different from the speed of individual waves and is crucial for understanding how waves carry energy and information.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
