<h3>Question 5</h3>
<div><p><p>Discuss effective mass of electrons and holes.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>The <strong>effective mass</strong> of an electron or hole is a concept used in solid-state physics to describe how electrons and holes move in a crystal lattice. It accounts for the interaction of electrons/holes with the periodic potential of the lattice, making them behave as if they have a different mass than their actual mass.</p>
<p><strong>Effective mass of electron:</strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>In a crystal lattice, electrons experience forces due to the periodic potential of the atoms. This changes their motion, making them behave as if they have an <strong>effective mass (<span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">me∗</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>)</strong>.</li>
<li>The effective mass is determined by the curvature of the electron&#8217;s energy band in the <strong>E-k diagram</strong> (energy vs. wave vector):<img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class=" wp-image-52494 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/Screenshot_2025-02-26_174516-removebg-preview.png?resize=82%2C58&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="82" height="58"><br />
where <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">ℏ</span></span> is the reduced Planck&#8217;s constant, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">E</span></span> is the energy, and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">k</span></span> is the wave vector.</li>
<li>If the band is steep (high curvature), the effective mass is small. If the band is flat (low curvature), the effective mass is large.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Effective mass of holes:</strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>A <strong>hole</strong> is the absence of an electron in the valence band. It behaves like a positively charged particle with an <strong>effective mass (<span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">mh∗</span></span>)</strong>.<img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class=" wp-image-52495 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/Screenshot_2025-02-26_174953-removebg-preview.png?resize=117%2C67&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="117" height="67"></li>
<li>The effective mass of a hole is also determined by the curvature of the valence band in the <strong>E-k diagram</strong>:</li>
<li>Holes typically have a larger effective mass than electrons because the valence band is usually flatter than the conduction band.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Importance of Effective mass:</strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>The effective mass determines how easily electrons and holes can move through the crystal lattice when an electric field is applied.</li>
<li>It affects properties like <strong>mobility</strong>, <strong>conductivity</strong>, and the behavior of semiconductors and devices like transistors and diodes.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<h3>Question 6</h3>
<div><p><p>Set up Schrodinger equation and discuss the wavefunction.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><h3><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><strong>Schrodinger Equation :</strong></span></h3>
<p>The <strong>Schrodinger equation</strong> is the fundamental equation of quantum mechanics. It describes how the <strong>wavefunction</strong> of a quantum system evolves over time. There are two forms: <strong>time-dependent</strong> and <strong>time-independent</strong>.</p>
<h4><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><strong>Time- dependent </strong><strong>Schrodinger Equation </strong></span></h4>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-52574 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/Screenshot_2025-02-27_210642-removebg-preview.png?resize=188%2C49&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="188" height="49">where:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">Ψ(r,t)</span></span> is the <strong>wavefunction</strong> of the system,</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">H^</span></span> is the <strong>Hamiltonian operator</strong> (total energy operator),</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord">ℏ</span></span></span></span> is the reduced Planck&#8217;s constant (<span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">ℏ=h/2π</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>),</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">r</span></span> represents the spatial coordinates,</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">t</span></span> is time.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Time-independent s</strong><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><strong>chrodinger Equation </strong></span></p>
<p>For stationary states (where the wavefunction does not change with time), the time-dependent equation simplifies to:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display ds-markdown-math"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">H^ψ(r)=Eψ(r),</span></span></span></p>
<p>where:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">ψ(r)</span></span> is the <strong>time-independent wavefunction</strong>,</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">E</span></span> is the energy of the system.</li>
</ul>
<p>The Hamiltonian operator <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">H^</span></span> is given by:</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-52576 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/Screenshot_2025-02-27_210713-removebg-preview.png?resize=203%2C59&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="203" height="59">where:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">m</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">m</span></span></span></span> is the mass of the particle,</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">∇2</span></span>is the Laplacian operator (second derivative with respect to space),</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">V(r)</span></span> is the potential energy.</li>
</ul>
<h3><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><strong>2. Wavefunction :</strong></span></h3>
<p>The <strong>wavefunction</strong> <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">Ψ(r,t)</span></span> (or <span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">ψ</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathbf">r</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></span></span> for stationary states) is a mathematical function that describes the quantum state of a system. It contains all the information about the system.</p>
<p><strong>Properties of the Wavefunction:</strong></p>
<ol start="1">
<li><strong>Probability Interpretation</strong>:
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>The square of the wavefunction <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">∣Ψ(r,t)∣<sup>2</sup></span></span> (or <span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord">∣</span><span class="mord mathnormal">ψ</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathbf">r</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mord">∣<sup>2</sup></span></span></span></span>) gives the <strong>probability density</strong> of finding the particle at position <span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathbf">r</span></span></span></span> at time <span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">t</span></span></span></span>.</li>
<li>The probability of finding the particle in a small volume <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">dV</span></span> is:<span class="katex-display ds-markdown-math"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">P(r,t) dV=∣Ψ(r,t)∣<sup>2</sup>  dV</span></span></span></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Normalization</strong>:
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>The wavefunction must be normalized, meaning the total probability of finding the particle somewhere in space is 1:<img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-52578 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/Screenshot_2025-02-27_210735-removebg-preview.png?resize=180%2C62&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="180" height="62"></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Superposition Principle</strong>:
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>If <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">Ψ1</span></span> and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">Ψ2</span></span> are solutions to the Schrödinger equation, then any linear combination <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">Ψ=c1Ψ1+c2Ψ2</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is also a solution.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Boundary Conditions</strong>:
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>The wavefunction must be <strong>continuous</strong> and <strong>smooth</strong> (its derivative must also be continuous) everywhere in space.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
